1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,152
Welcome to the complete beginner's guide to Fluent Agents Studio.

2
00:00:04,152 --> 00:00:10,956
This guide assumes you have never opened the app, never made a voice-over, and never edited a video in your life.

3
00:00:10,956 --> 00:00:11,679
That's fine.

4
00:00:11,679 --> 00:00:16,917
By the end of these twelve minutes you'll know exactly what you'll see on every screen,

5
00:00:16,917 --> 00:00:24,504
what every button does, and how to go from a web article to a finished, narrated video without touching a single editing tool.

6
00:00:24,504 --> 00:00:26,992
First, what the studio actually makes.

7
00:00:26,992 --> 00:00:31,903
You give it something to read — a link to a web article, or a PDF document.

8
00:00:31,903 --> 00:00:37,010
It reads that source and produces, on its own: a spoken audio episode, where a

9
00:00:37,010 --> 00:00:42,838
natural-sounding computer voice — that's what a voice-over is — narrates or discusses the

10
00:00:42,838 --> 00:00:48,404
material; a slideshow, meaning a set of slides that change on screen in time with the

11
00:00:48,404 --> 00:00:55,606
voice; a video file of the same thing that you can upload anywhere; and a PowerPoint you can present yourself.

12
00:00:55,606 --> 00:00:59,666
Your entire job is to say what you want in ordinary sentences.

13
00:00:59,666 --> 00:01:03,726
Keep that in mind throughout: you never edit anything by hand.

14
00:01:03,726 --> 00:01:05,952
You describe, the studio produces.

15
00:01:05,952 --> 00:01:08,659
So let's take your first look at the studio.

16
00:01:08,659 --> 00:01:13,888
The studio's web address, fluentagents.com, greets you with its front door: a landing

17
00:01:13,888 --> 00:01:19,855
page where this very guide plays as a video, with real example productions to explore beneath it.

18
00:01:19,855 --> 00:01:26,376
Press the amber Open the Studio button there and you're in the workbench — which is where our tour begins.

19
00:01:26,376 --> 00:01:30,627
Inside the studio, you're looking at a dark page split into two areas.

20
00:01:30,627 --> 00:01:38,766
Down the left side runs a narrow column — that's the library, the list of everything you've ever produced, with a search box above it.

21
00:01:38,766 --> 00:01:42,228
Nothing in the library disappears when you close the app.

22
00:01:42,228 --> 00:01:47,633
At the top of that column sit two buttons: an amber one labeled New Generation — amber is

23
00:01:47,633 --> 00:01:53,038
the studio's signature orange-gold color, and that button is where every project begins —

24
00:01:53,038 --> 00:01:56,682
and a plain one labeled Templates, which we'll come back to.

25
00:01:56,682 --> 00:02:02,088
The large area to the right is your workspace, and it opens on a form titled "From source

26
00:02:02,088 --> 00:02:06,096
to sound." That form is what you're seeing on the slide right now.

27
00:02:06,096 --> 00:02:10,961
Now let's fill in the form, top to bottom. It reads in three boxes.

28
00:02:10,961 --> 00:02:13,285
The first box is labeled Source.

29
00:02:13,285 --> 00:02:18,803
It has two small round buttons — URL and PDF upload — and a wide text field.

30
00:02:18,803 --> 00:02:24,176
Paste a web address into the field, or click PDF upload and choose a file.

31
00:02:24,176 --> 00:02:30,131
Easier still: drag a PDF from your computer anywhere onto that box and it attaches

32
00:02:30,131 --> 00:02:34,560
itself, showing the file's name in amber so you know it took.

33
00:02:34,560 --> 00:02:39,216
The second box, Production, is where you make the three decisions that matter.

34
00:02:39,216 --> 00:02:44,468
The Mode menu decides the kind of listening experience: Podcast turns your source into a

35
00:02:44,468 --> 00:02:49,482
lively conversation between two hosts; Summary gives you one narrator delivering the

36
00:02:49,482 --> 00:02:55,630
short version in a few minutes; Readout is the whole document read aloud faithfully, like an audiobook.

37
00:02:55,630 --> 00:03:00,882
The Run Until menu decides how far the studio goes before pausing for you: choose Script

38
00:03:00,882 --> 00:03:08,283
Draft and it stops after writing the words — the cheap, safe place to start; choose Full Production and it goes all the way.

39
00:03:08,283 --> 00:03:13,297
And the Audience field is a plain-text box where you describe who will listen — type

40
00:03:13,297 --> 00:03:18,072
"complete beginners" or "busy executives who want numbers," and the writing, the

41
00:03:18,072 --> 00:03:22,191
examples, and the level of explanation all shift to fit those people.

42
00:03:22,191 --> 00:03:27,503
Below these sit optional personality fields — describe a host as "an enthusiastic teacher

43
00:03:27,503 --> 00:03:34,128
who loves analogies" and that is exactly who you'll hear — and voice pickers, which you can safely leave empty.

44
00:03:34,128 --> 00:03:37,858
The third box, Slides and Captions, chooses your outputs.

45
00:03:37,858 --> 00:03:42,897
Slides picks the formats: web slideshow, video, PowerPoint, or a combination.

46
00:03:42,897 --> 00:03:48,198
Captions are the spoken words shown as text on screen — pick Burned to print them

47
00:03:48,198 --> 00:03:53,303
permanently into the video, or Toggle so each viewer can turn them on and off.

48
00:03:53,303 --> 00:03:59,061
Animations, when switched on, makes slide content glide in element by element instead of

49
00:03:59,061 --> 00:04:03,708
appearing all at once — you're seeing that effect on these very slides.

50
00:04:03,708 --> 00:04:08,616
Then the amber Start Generation button at the bottom sets it all in motion.

51
00:04:08,616 --> 00:04:12,230
Now let's talk about the project page and the four lights.

52
00:04:12,230 --> 00:04:16,156
The moment you start, the studio opens your project's own page.

53
00:04:16,156 --> 00:04:23,820
The project's title sits large at the top, with a small status capsule on the right that says whether it's working or done.

54
00:04:23,820 --> 00:04:29,179
And just below the title runs the most important thing on the page: a horizontal strip

55
00:04:29,179 --> 00:04:34,102
with four dots connected by a line, labeled Script, Slides, Voice, and Outputs.

56
00:04:34,102 --> 00:04:39,586
Think of it as four stations on an assembly line — first the words get written, then the

57
00:04:39,586 --> 00:04:44,695
visuals get designed, then the voice gets recorded, then everything gets packaged.

58
00:04:44,695 --> 00:04:50,491
A solid amber dot means that station is finished; a pulsing dot means it's working right now.

59
00:04:50,491 --> 00:04:54,292
Each label is clickable and takes you to that station's page.

60
00:04:54,292 --> 00:04:59,775
The studio's whole philosophy lives in this strip: you can stop at any station, say what

61
00:04:59,775 --> 00:05:03,888
you'd like changed, and everything after it updates automatically.

62
00:05:03,888 --> 00:05:06,083
Let's visit station one: the script.

63
00:05:06,083 --> 00:05:11,267
Click Script — the first light — and you see the transcript: every sentence the voice

64
00:05:11,267 --> 00:05:18,036
will speak, laid out as a numbered list, each line carrying a small letter badge showing which speaker says it.

65
00:05:18,036 --> 00:05:23,402
What's on the slide now is a real script page. Read it the way a director reads a draft.

66
00:05:23,402 --> 00:05:28,708
When you want changes, look at the bottom of the page: there's a large text box labeled

67
00:05:28,708 --> 00:05:32,793
Revision Instructions with an amber Revise Script button beside it.

68
00:05:32,793 --> 00:05:38,038
Type what you want in plain words — "Open with a question instead of an announcement,"

69
00:05:38,038 --> 00:05:43,282
"Cut the part about pricing," "Make the second host funnier" — and the studio rewrites

70
00:05:43,282 --> 00:05:47,978
exactly what you asked for, leaving every other line word-for-word untouched.

71
00:05:47,978 --> 00:05:53,222
A revision takes about a minute, and this is the single most important habit to learn:

72
00:05:53,222 --> 00:05:57,552
polish the words while they're cheap, before any audio or video exists.

73
00:05:57,552 --> 00:05:59,369
On to station two: the slides.

74
00:05:59,369 --> 00:06:05,305
Click Slides and the deck appears as a grid of small cards, one card per slide, like a storyboard.

75
00:06:05,305 --> 00:06:10,393
Each card shows the slide's number, the moment in the audio when it will appear, its

76
00:06:10,393 --> 00:06:16,390
title and bullet points, and — when the slide carries a picture or a chart — a small preview of it.

77
00:06:16,390 --> 00:06:21,720
The pictures aren't decoration pulled from a stock library: the studio lifts real images

78
00:06:21,720 --> 00:06:29,715
out of your source document, and it draws its own charts, timelines, and diagrams whenever the material contains data worth showing.

79
00:06:29,715 --> 00:06:34,803
Scroll to the bottom of this page and you'll find the Asset Inventory — a gallery of

80
00:06:34,803 --> 00:06:42,072
every image and figure with a note saying exactly which slide uses each one, so nothing in your production is a mystery.

81
00:06:42,072 --> 00:06:47,106
Slides revise exactly like the script — same kind of box at the bottom, same plain

82
00:06:47,106 --> 00:06:52,140
English: "Make every title a question." "Merge slides three and four." And if your

83
00:06:52,140 --> 00:06:57,481
company has a visual identity, click that Templates button back in the top-left corner:

84
00:06:57,481 --> 00:07:04,847
it opens a page where you upload a PowerPoint template, a style-guide document, or even a screenshot of slides you like.

85
00:07:04,847 --> 00:07:11,477
The studio reads the colors and fonts out of whatever you give it and applies them to everything it renders.

86
00:07:11,477 --> 00:07:17,616
Save the files once as a named set, and every future project can use it from a simple dropdown menu.

87
00:07:17,616 --> 00:07:22,217
Now for station three: the voice — the part that sounds hardest and isn't.

88
00:07:22,217 --> 00:07:26,009
Each slide card carries a tiny play symbol in its top corner.

89
00:07:26,009 --> 00:07:31,480
Click it and the screen dims: your slide appears large in the middle, and a slim control

90
00:07:31,480 --> 00:07:37,822
bar sits beneath it with pause, previous and next arrows, a progress line, and an auto-advance switch.

91
00:07:37,822 --> 00:07:44,226
What you hear is precisely the stretch of narration that belongs to that slide — not the whole episode.

92
00:07:44,226 --> 00:07:49,448
That's what's on screen now: one slide, under review, with its own segment of voice.

93
00:07:49,448 --> 00:07:54,795
Step through your whole production this way; it's how you catch the slide that arrives

94
00:07:54,795 --> 00:07:58,152
one beat too late or the sentence that needs more air.

95
00:07:58,152 --> 00:08:03,641
When something sounds off, go to the Voice page — the third light — and give instructions

96
00:08:03,641 --> 00:08:09,131
that mention line numbers from the script: "Line 4, slow down ten percent and pause after

97
00:08:09,131 --> 00:08:14,435
the question." "Pronounce Nguyen as win, everywhere." The written transcript keeps the

98
00:08:14,435 --> 00:08:20,911
correct spelling; only the pronunciation changes, and the audio re-records itself within a minute or two.

99
00:08:20,911 --> 00:08:26,401
And if a slide appears at the wrong moment, every card has a small offset box: type minus

100
00:08:26,401 --> 00:08:33,432
two to bring it in two seconds earlier, press Apply Timing, and the visuals re-sync without re-recording anything.

101
00:08:33,432 --> 00:08:37,481
And finally, station four: the outputs — the packaging department.

102
00:08:37,481 --> 00:08:42,512
At the top sits an amber Render Production button with menus beside it for slides,

103
00:08:42,512 --> 00:08:50,119
captions and animations — press it and the studio assembles everything from your current script, slides and voice direction.

104
00:08:50,119 --> 00:08:55,580
Below, each finished file gets its own card: the Audio card holds the episode with a play

105
00:08:55,580 --> 00:09:00,733
bar and a download link; the Transcript card shows the full text with a timestamp on

106
00:09:00,733 --> 00:09:06,070
every line; the Web Slideshow card opens the synced presentation — a single file, sound

107
00:09:06,070 --> 00:09:11,347
included, that you can send to anyone; the Video card previews the movie file; and the

108
00:09:11,347 --> 00:09:16,745
PowerPoint card downloads a deck that carries the narration as speaker notes under every

109
00:09:16,745 --> 00:09:21,531
slide, so you can present it yourself and read what the voice would have said.

110
00:09:21,531 --> 00:09:24,230
There's one more card on this page: YouTube.

111
00:09:24,230 --> 00:09:29,445
Once you've connected your channel — a one-time, five-minute setup the card walks you

112
00:09:29,445 --> 00:09:32,574
through — publishing your video is a single button.

113
00:09:32,574 --> 00:09:39,936
It uploads as private, so you review it on YouTube before anyone else can see it, and the link is saved on your project.

114
00:09:39,936 --> 00:09:41,657
One honest note about money.

115
00:09:41,657 --> 00:09:46,452
The studio's writing and design run on a paid artificial-intelligence service.

116
00:09:46,452 --> 00:09:51,309
Next to each project's title you'll find a small capsule reading something like

117
00:09:51,309 --> 00:09:59,424
"approximately forty cents model spend" — that's the project's real running cost, usually well under a dollar for a full production.

118
00:09:59,424 --> 00:10:04,895
The studio also makes repeat revisions cheap: when you iterate several times within a few

119
00:10:04,895 --> 00:10:09,567
minutes, the repeated material is billed at roughly a tenth of normal price.

120
00:10:09,567 --> 00:10:13,440
So work the way good producers work anyway — in focused bursts.

121
00:10:13,440 --> 00:10:17,431
Let's bring it all together — the whole method in one breath.

122
00:10:17,431 --> 00:10:23,255
Start a project with a source, a mode, and an audience, and run it only until the script.

123
00:10:23,255 --> 00:10:28,293
Read the script and revise it in plain sentences until it says what you mean.

124
00:10:28,293 --> 00:10:33,135
Shape the slides the same way, with your template if you have one. Render.

125
00:10:33,135 --> 00:10:40,398
Review slide by slide with the little play buttons, fix pronunciation and pacing by line number, nudge timings.

126
00:10:40,398 --> 00:10:43,669
Collect five finished files from the Outputs page.

127
00:10:43,669 --> 00:10:49,166
Notice what never happened: no audio editing, no slide designing, no video software.

128
00:10:49,166 --> 00:10:57,345
The production skills are built into the studio — the only skill you brought was knowing what you wanted to say, and to whom.

129
00:10:57,345 --> 00:11:06,112
Everything you've just watched and heard, including these very slides and this voice, was produced by the studio this guide describes.

130
00:11:06,112 --> 00:11:09,384
Your turn: one pasted link, and you're a producer.
